gland, United Kingdom","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Corbet was born in 1385, in Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales. She married Robert Corbet II about 1406, in Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1385–":"1385–Surnud","1381–1438":"1381–1438","1407–1488":"1407–1488","1407–1487":"1407–1487","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","about 1407":"umbes 1407","1488":"1488","1487":"1487","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","ABT 1406":"umbes 1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leigh